  "final_analysis": "In managing hyperthyroidism during the first trimester of pregnancy, the primary concern is the safety of the drug for both the mother and the developing fetus. Methimazole and Carbimazole are known to have higher risks of teratogenic effects, which can lead to congenital malformations. Propylthiouracil (PTU), on the other hand, is generally considered safer during the first trimester due to its lower risk of causing such effects. Perchlorate is not commonly used as a first-line treatment due to its lesser effectiveness and limited study in this context. Therefore, based on the consensus in medical guidelines and literature, Propylthiouracil is the preferred choice for treating hyperthyroidism in the first trimester of pregnancy.",
